Subject:    <a href="?t=95837890400026&r=1&w=2">Has anyone used the TXT record?</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837785200039&r=1&w=2">fin () uf ! msc ! umn ! edu (Craig Finseth)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198810">1988-10-28 14:47:24</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026994&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026994&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We have a network administration program that would like to use TXT
records (it currently uses the non-standard but "supported" UINFO
records).  Our format is:

					for...

	IN	UINFO	"DA:xxxx"	DECNET address
	IN	UINFO	"EA:xxxx"	Ethernet address
	IN	UINFO	"HL:xxxx"	host location (US Mail address/phone)
	IN	UINFO	"ML:xxxx"	maintainer location ("   ")
	IN	UINFO	"MI:xxxx"	maintainer info (Internet address)

any RR that doesn't match one of these is perserved.

(All of that info was for background: we do NOT expect that this
format be standardized in any fashion.)  What we really want is some
RR be available that can hold up to, say, 255 bytes of arbitrary data.

Craig A. Finseth			fin@uc.msc.umn.edu [CAF13]
Minnesota Supercomputer Center, Inc.	(612) 624-3375

